Troubleshooting Tips
Issue 1: Permission Denied Errors

Verify script has execute permissions: chmod +x script.sh
Check file ownership: ls -l filename
Ensure you're in correct directory: pwd
Issue 2: Policy Not Applied

Verify policy file format matches specification
Check for syntax errors in configuration
Ensure no trailing spaces in policy entries
Issue 3: Monitoring Not Detecting Changes

Recreate baseline: ./scripts/access_monitor.sh baseline
Verify baseline file exists: ls -l ~/zerotrust-lab/logs/baseline.txt
Check file paths are absolute, not relative
Issue 4: Scripts Not Finding Files

Use absolute paths: $HOME/zerotrust-lab/...
Verify directory structure: tree ~/zerotrust-lab
Check environment variables: echo $HOME
Conclusion
This lab provided hands-on experience implementing Zero Trust security principles in a Linux environment. Students created policy management systems, applied least privilege access controls, and developed monitoring capabilities. These skills are fundamental to modern cybersecurity practices.

Key Takeaways:

Zero Trust requires explicit verification for every access request
Least privilege minimizes potential security impact
Continuous monitoring detects unauthorized changes
Automation ensures consistent policy enforcement
